The skill is a major shift, and that's the
shift I wanted to be talking about today.

25
00:01:29,489 --> 00:01:34,429
Okay, we resolved the speed problem,
but in doing so, we have uncovered

26
00:01:34,449 --> 00:01:38,889
a much harder problem, like how
do you trust what AI builds?

27
00:01:39,649 --> 00:01:45,489
And for years, the database team primarily
constrained by the capability and how

28
00:01:45,529 --> 00:01:50,389
to automate deployments fast enough,
how to manage migration, and can the

29
00:01:50,429 --> 00:01:52,070
pipeline scale with the business demand?

30
00:01:52,909 --> 00:01:57,729
Earlier, velocity was the KPI,
but now AI change the equations.

31
00:01:58,449 --> 00:02:02,629
AI tools can generate schemas much
faster, optimize queries, write

32
00:02:02,669 --> 00:02:07,450
migration scripts, and automate
operational workflows almost instantly.

33
00:02:07,990 --> 00:02:11,090
So the bottleneck is no
longer can we build it.

34
00:02:11,610 --> 00:02:13,770
Rather, should we build it this way?

35
00:02:14,370 --> 00:02:18,990
Because fast output is not the
same like a trustworthy output.

36
00:02:19,710 --> 00:02:24,190
In database systems, inconsistencies
compound over a period of time that

37
00:02:24,250 --> 00:02:29,430
quietly degrade the performance in
which we cannot even notice it until

38
00:02:29,470 --> 00:02:31,750
it's a major issue or major bottleneck.

39
00:02:32,470 --> 00:02:38,350
And one incorrect schema decisions
can survey for years, and a poorly

40
00:02:38,790 --> 00:02:42,230
reviewed migration can cascade
into different production systems.

41
00:02:42,730 --> 00:02:45,350
I call this emerging
problem as experience debt.

42
00:02:46,049 --> 00:02:49,429
Similar to technical debt, but
more dangerous in AI systems

43
00:02:49,749 --> 00:02:52,290
because it accumulates invisibly.

44
00:02:52,309 --> 00:02:54,369
And here are the three major symptoms.

45
00:02:55,230 --> 00:02:56,969
And first one is inconsistency creep.

46
00:02:57,609 --> 00:03:01,029
Without governance, every engineer
interacts differently with AI tools.

47
00:03:01,690 --> 00:03:05,368
They build different prompts, make
different assumptions, and create

48
00:03:05,410 --> 00:03:07,170
more different validation standards.

49
00:03:07,769 --> 00:03:11,959
Eventually, the team end up building
and sharing an inconsistent engineering

50
00:03:12,010 --> 00:03:16,690
language, and that is going to
create a ch-chaos among the teams.

51
00:03:17,450 --> 00:03:19,630
The second is amplified data risk.

52
00:03:20,130 --> 00:03:24,529
AI-generated SQL may appear
syntactically correct but may end up

53
00:03:24,570 --> 00:03:29,070
introducing security vulnerabilities,
index regressions, locking issues,

54
00:03:29,329 --> 00:03:31,109
or perhaps integrity failures.

55
00:03:31,829 --> 00:03:33,789
The third is erosion of trust.

56
00:03:34,309 --> 00:03:37,309
This probably the biggest problem
compared to all the three.

57
00:03:38,009 --> 00:03:42,509
When engineers stop understanding
on why AI has produced certain

58
00:03:42,529 --> 00:03:45,249
output, they move into two extremes.

59
00:03:45,948 --> 00:03:52,489
Either they blind-blindly trust or reject
it totally, and either of it leads to

60
00:03:52,529 --> 00:03:55,149
both technical and operational failures.

61
00:03:56,029 --> 00:03:59,329
And this is where HAX actually comes in.

62
00:04:00,129 --> 00:04:05,969
HAX stands for human and AI experience,
a structured approach for adopting AI

63
00:04:06,029 --> 00:04:08,669
intentionally across DevOp operations.

64
00:04:09,589 --> 00:04:14,309
HAX also defines the lines between
where should humans retain authority

65
00:04:15,029 --> 00:04:18,529
and where should AI accelerate
work, and how accountability flows

66
00:04:18,569 --> 00:04:19,839
across the delivery lifecycle.

67
00:04:20,539 --> 00:04:22,900
This framework classifies
the responsibility in two

68
00:04:22,919 --> 00:04:25,640
distinct layers: HAX and IAX.

69
00:04:26,419 --> 00:04:32,219
HAX is where humans and AI operate with
clearly defined expectations HX defined

70
00:04:32,260 --> 00:04:36,780
areas where human experience is not
compromised by automated experience.

71
00:04:37,439 --> 00:04:40,979
End of the day, it is a user who
uses the system should find it

72
00:04:41,020 --> 00:04:43,059
easy, intuitive, and friendly.

73
00:04:43,639 --> 00:04:47,919
These are not the tasks that AI can't do
it, but a human judgment is fundamentally

74
00:04:47,960 --> 00:04:52,479
required because the decisions carry
long-term organizational consequences.

75
00:04:53,039 --> 00:04:57,599
For example, in system architecture
AI can recommend scaling patterns,

76
00:04:58,199 --> 00:05:01,739
but that does not understand
organizational politics or future

77
00:05:01,819 --> 00:05:05,279
acquisition plans or business shape--
business strategy shapes, et cetera.

78
00:05:06,189 --> 00:05:09,459
And in data modeling, schema
design is not just a structure.

79
00:05:09,519 --> 00:05:11,019
It encodes the business meaning.

80
00:05:11,659 --> 00:05:14,879
A naming convention mistake today
becomes a reporting problem for

81
00:05:14,919 --> 00:05:16,499
the next four or five years.

82
00:05:17,319 --> 00:05:21,759
And the governance is also another
critical domain where compliance,

83
00:05:22,019 --> 00:05:25,979
access control, data classification,
audit accountability cannot be

84
00:05:26,039 --> 00:05:27,499
simply delegated to the systems.

85
00:05:28,079 --> 00:05:30,739
It requires human interventions
and the human thought.

86
00:05:31,519 --> 00:05:33,529
And finally, the critical reasoning.

87
00:05:34,209 --> 00:05:38,479
During production incidents humans
synthesize the context from many

88
00:05:38,499 --> 00:05:42,610
sources from the team history, risk
tolerance business urgency, and

89
00:05:42,680 --> 00:05:44,780
customer impact, and all of these stuff.

90
00:05:45,260 --> 00:05:48,159
All these things cannot be
managed by the AI alone.

91
00:05:48,419 --> 00:05:51,820
It requires the fundamental
human thought process.

92
00:05:52,320 --> 00:05:55,520
In a nutshell, humans
decide, and AI elevates it.

93
00:05:56,420 --> 00:06:00,860
Now, let's look at the facets
of AX, the AI experience layer.

94
00:06:01,800 --> 00:06:05,900
The six facets defines where AI
actually adds value at the highest

95
00:06:06,480 --> 00:06:07,740
across the DevOps lifecycle.

96
00:06:08,610 --> 00:06:13,830
During detection, AI excels at anomaly
detections, identifying drift patterns

97
00:06:14,210 --> 00:06:16,630
which humans most likely miss all this.

98
00:06:17,490 --> 00:06:23,450
While predicting, AI can focus migration
risks, capacity growth query specs, and

99
00:06:23,530 --> 00:06:27,680
even create or limited bottlenecks Scale
is where the repetitive operational

100
00:06:27,740 --> 00:06:32,440
work becomes highly automated, like
index recommendations, connection

101
00:06:32,520 --> 00:06:34,700
pooling, and pipeline orchestration.

102
00:06:35,620 --> 00:06:40,260
During synthesize, AI does an
incredible job in consolidating the

103
00:06:40,320 --> 00:06:44,730
information about telemetry, logs
documentation, and it can even change

104
00:06:45,350 --> 00:06:49,900
history into a useful and operational
information or knowledge repository.

105
00:06:50,400 --> 00:06:55,340
While executing, AI can automate
deployment workflows and migrations,

106
00:06:55,441 --> 00:06:59,200
but only within the governance
boundaries which are defined

107
00:06:59,240 --> 00:07:00,920
by the humans or the users.

108
00:07:01,520 --> 00:07:02,960
And finally, ethics.

109
00:07:03,480 --> 00:07:07,060
This is an increasingly important
aspect, especially in an enterprise

110
00:07:07,120 --> 00:07:11,839
environments where transparency becomes
a part of engineering reliability.

111
00:07:12,800 --> 00:07:16,600
Coming to the crux, HAIX operates
better through six stages across

112
00:07:16,660 --> 00:07:18,160
three phases of delivery methodology.

113
00:07:18,520 --> 00:07:20,600
That is a discovery,
design, and development.

114
00:07:21,480 --> 00:07:25,420
Most organizations adopt AI tools
first and think about governance later.

115
00:07:26,200 --> 00:07:28,060
However, HAIX reverses it.

116
00:07:28,800 --> 00:07:32,320
It defines accountability first
and then accelerate executions.

117
00:07:33,300 --> 00:07:34,500
Let's dive into the phases.

118
00:07:35,330 --> 00:07:38,940
Discovery is where most
human-centric activities are engaged.

119
00:07:39,600 --> 00:07:42,890
It requires human-to-human connections
to understand the ground reality,

120
00:07:43,520 --> 00:07:48,040
emotions, business context, apart from
identifying the constraints and the

121
00:07:48,100 --> 00:07:50,260
risk typically the users are facing it.

122
00:07:51,000 --> 00:07:53,640
And this is managed through
stakeholder interviews, system

123
00:07:53,680 --> 00:07:55,720
inventories, and the risk assessments.

124
00:07:56,520 --> 00:08:00,220
At the same time, AI assists this
phase by synthesizing information

125
00:08:00,420 --> 00:08:04,640
and generate insights out of raw
data and other surfacing patterns

126
00:08:05,060 --> 00:08:06,910
typically the humans might miss.

127
00:08:07,410 --> 00:08:12,610
Moving on to the design, and design
is where humans and AI collaborate.

128
00:08:12,710 --> 00:08:16,810
The human engineers define and own
the overall experience, build schemas

129
00:08:16,850 --> 00:08:20,670
and architecture decisions, and AI
assists by running the validation

130
00:08:20,750 --> 00:08:25,070
checks, suggest index strategies, diff
crafting pipeline and scaffolding.

131
00:08:25,670 --> 00:08:28,430
But nothing move forward
without the human approval.

132
00:08:28,990 --> 00:08:32,750
Think of AI as a junior engineer
who does the research but

133
00:08:33,149 --> 00:08:34,610
shouldn't be making the final call.

134
00:08:35,060 --> 00:08:36,490
All lies with the human engineers.

135
00:08:37,490 --> 00:08:41,170
Moving on to the development, and
here is where the AI takes the lead.

136
00:08:41,770 --> 00:08:46,510
AI drives migration execution, schema
versioning, and deployment automation,

137
00:08:47,170 --> 00:08:51,880
and human engineers monitors and retain
and override the authority at every step.

138
00:08:52,540 --> 00:08:57,260
In the final stage, AI synthesizes all
the telemetry and observability data.

139
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:01,240
Engineers validate it and feed the
corrections back into the system.

140
00:09:01,900 --> 00:09:05,380
That feedback loop is constantly
happening, and this is what

141
00:09:05,600 --> 00:09:08,411
makes this a living process
instead of a one-time setup.

142
00:09:08,911 --> 00:09:13,560
One of the most important aspects in
HAIX is the clarity of boundaries, what

143
00:09:13,610 --> 00:09:16,970
human owns and what AI is used for.

144
00:09:17,031 --> 00:09:21,210
When AI responsibilities becomes
ambiguous, teams started failing.

145
00:09:21,790 --> 00:09:25,570
If everyone assumes AI is
responsible, then no one owns outcome.

146
00:09:26,390 --> 00:09:31,110
And that's the reason HAIX explicitly
maps where human intervention and

147
00:09:31,151 --> 00:09:35,370
approval is mandatory and where
AI makes a safe contribution.

148
00:09:36,131 --> 00:09:41,011
This transforms AI from a black box
into a governed engineering participant.

149
00:09:41,511 --> 00:09:44,570
Here is the most important part
many people tend to overlook,

150
00:09:45,151 --> 00:09:46,511
which is knowledge artifacts.

151
00:09:47,111 --> 00:09:50,450
Most organizations underestimate the
value of standardized knowledge artifacts.

152
00:09:51,151 --> 00:09:55,011
Without the standardized artifacts,
every engineer end up creating their

153
00:09:55,050 --> 00:09:59,310
own prompting style, define their
own validation logic, and build

154
00:09:59,330 --> 00:10:01,231
their own AI workflow patterns.

155
00:10:02,070 --> 00:10:06,190
To overcome operational challenges,
knowledge artifacts has to be standardized

156
00:10:06,670 --> 00:10:10,851
and establish new guidelines on how
project teams adopt AI with curated

157
00:10:10,950 --> 00:10:15,261
prompt libraries runbooks, and
tool-specific interaction patterns.

158
00:10:16,241 --> 00:10:20,101
In the future, an organization's
competitive advantage is not just on

159
00:10:20,141 --> 00:10:24,881
the AI models, but it's on the knowledge
re-- knowledge artifacts and the

160
00:10:24,901 --> 00:10:27,141
organization memory they have defined.

161
00:10:27,641 --> 00:10:31,980
Here are some of the key takeaways that
will leave you with three final ideas.

162
00:10:32,560 --> 00:10:35,960
First, speed is not the
goal, but reliable speed is.

163
00:10:36,560 --> 00:10:40,501
The winning ones are those who
not just move faster, but also

164
00:10:40,521 --> 00:10:42,080
know what they are shipping.

165
00:10:42,790 --> 00:10:46,920
And second, humans and AI
are better together, but only

166
00:10:46,940 --> 00:10:47,901
with the clear boundaries.

167
00:10:48,540 --> 00:10:52,281
Either we let AI do everything
or we don't trust with anything.

168
00:10:52,861 --> 00:10:53,861
The answer is in the middle.

169
00:10:54,361 --> 00:10:57,621
Define exactly what
each is responsible for.

170
00:10:58,320 --> 00:11:00,220
Third, start where you are.

171
00:11:00,560 --> 00:11:02,560
You don't need a perfect
framework on day one.

172
00:11:03,101 --> 00:11:06,361
A shared prompt library and a
validation checklist will get

173
00:11:06,401 --> 00:11:08,460
you further than what you think.

174
00:11:09,121 --> 00:11:12,190
Human and AI capabilities
are not competing systems,

175
00:11:12,820 --> 00:11:13,861
but complementary system.

176
00:11:14,161 --> 00:11:19,341
We have to understand the balance between
this and work together for larger benefit.

177
00:11:20,161 --> 00:11:23,741
Organizations that succeed with AI are
not necessarily the ones automating

178
00:11:23,761 --> 00:11:28,341
the fastest, but creating the clear
accountability structures between

179
00:11:28,361 --> 00:11:29,881
the humans and intelligent systems.

180
00:11:30,401 --> 00:11:32,001
We finally come to the closure.

181
00:11:32,440 --> 00:11:33,601
Thanks everyone for your time.

182
00:11:34,101 --> 00:11:38,161
Start asking, "Should we build this
way?" instead of, "Can we build

183
00:11:38,221 --> 00:11:42,241
it?" In whatever the case, HAIX
is the way to answer the question.

184
00:11:42,901 --> 00:11:44,201
I hope this session is useful to you.

185
00:11:45,021 --> 00:11:49,101
Thank you once again and glad to
answer any specific questions.

186
00:11:49,141 --> 00:11:49,420
Thank you.

